Abstract

Customer churn is a significant challenge for banks and financial institutions, as retaining existing customers is often more cost-effective than acquiring new ones. This study aims to analyze key factors contributing to customer churn using real-world banking data obtained from Kaggle Bank Customer Churn â Kaggle.com. By leveraging Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) and machine learning techniques, we identify patterns that influence customer retention. Various models, including logistic regression, decision trees, and ensemble learning methods, are evaluated to determine their effectiveness in predicting customer churn. The findings of this study can help banks implement data-driven strategies to enhance customer satisfaction and loyalty, ultimately improving retention rates.

Introduction

In the modern banking sector, customer retention is a key determinant of long-term profitability. The loss of customers, known as customer churn, can negatively impact financial stability, making it crucial for banks to understand the underlying reasons why customers choose to leave. With increasing competition in the financial industry, the ability to predict churn and proactively address potential causes has become a strategic priority for banks.

This research explores customer churn in banking using a dataset from Kaggle Bank Customer Churn â Kaggle.com. The study applies Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) to uncover trends in customer behavior and employs machine learning models to predict churn with high accuracy. Factors such as demographic attributes, transaction patterns, and banking services usage are considered to determine their influence on customer retention.

The primary objectives of this study include: - Identifying key features contributing to customer churn. - Comparing different machine learning models for churn prediction. - Providing actionable insights for financial institutions to improve customer retention strategies.

Through this research, we aim to bridge the gap between raw data and actionable business decisions, equipping banks with predictive tools to minimize customer attrition and enhance long-term customer relationships.

1 Objectives

  1. Understand the factors leading to customer churn.
  2. Perform Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) to uncover trends.
  3. Apply machine learning models to predict churn.
  4. Evaluate the models for accuracy and interpretability.

2 Data Overview

The dataset is available on https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/sandiledesmondmfazi/bank-customer-churn.

The dataset contains customer information, including:

  • Demographics (e.g., age, gender, geography)
  • Account details (e.g., balance, number of products)
  • Transaction history (e.g., credit score, tenure, estimated salary)
  • Churn indicator (i.e., whether a customer left the bank)

3 Data Preprocessing

To prepare the data for analysis, the following preprocessing steps were applied:

  1. Handling Missing Values - Checked for missing data and handled appropriately.
  2. Encoding Categorical Variables - Used OneHotEncoding for categorical features like Geography and Gender.
  3. Feature Scaling - Applied StandardScaler for numerical variables.
  4. Train-Test Split - Divided the dataset into 80% training and 20% testing.

4 Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

Key observations from EDA:

4.1 Churn Rate

  • Approximately 20% of customers churned.
  • Churn was higher among younger customers and less active members.

4.2 Credit Score vs.Â Churn

  • Customers with lower credit scores were more likely to leave the bank.

4.3 Balance Distribution

  • Many customers with zero balance still retained their accounts.
  • A significant portion of customers with high balances also churned.

4.4 Effect of Geography

  • Customers from Germany had a higher churn rate compared to France and Spain.

5.4 Churn Analysis

5.4.1 Churn Analysis Feedback

  • Credit Score and Outstanding Loans have a slight negative correlation (higher credit score = fewer loans).

  • Balance and Number of Products show a mild positive correlation.

  • Churn Flag has low correlation with most numerical features (indicating churn might be influenced by categorical factors like occupation or marital status).

5.4.2 Churn Analysis feeback

  • Only ~12.2% of customers churned.

  • This suggests imbalanced data, which could affect churn prediction models.

  • NumOfProducts & NumComplaints have clear peaks, indicating common values.

8 Feature Importance

The most important factors influencing churn:

  1. Number of Products - Customers with only one product had higher churn rates.
  2. Balance - Higher balance customers were less likely to churn.
  3. Age - Older customers were more loyal.
  4. IsActiveMember - Active members had a lower churn probability.

9 Conclusion & Recommendations

  1. Target Customers with One Product
    • Offer incentives for multi-product subscriptions.
  2. Improve Retention Strategies for German Customers
    • Identify reasons for higher churn in Germany and tailor offers accordingly.
  3. Enhance Customer Engagement
    • Encourage customers to become active members through rewards.
  4. Monitor High-Balance Customers
    • Prevent churn by offering personalized services.
  5. Refine Credit Score Policies
    • Assist lower credit score customers with better financial solutions.
